<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-07-14T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-07-14T06:00:00-05:00" n="441" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d441">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/3390: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Crane</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-07-14T19:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">July 14,
                                            1920—7 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 10:17
                                    p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>184. The President has issued a conventional mandate ordering troops
                                of contending sides to return to their original posts, thus saving
                                the people from miseries of war. Will probably be entirely
                                disregarded. Joint telegram opposing Tuan received from the eight
                                military governors whose union seems complete. Martial law is
                                proclaimed in Peking by Tuan officials acting without President’s
                                approbation.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Crane</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>